node.text: This week Zach, our Quality Manager, helps to answer two of your questions: can you age saison and wild beers; and what is the best glassware for a lager beer? Have a beer question of your own? Let us know and we may feature it on Quality Time with Allagash.

node.title: Quality Time with Allagash - Aging saison and lager beer glassware

node.text:
Want to enjoy a perfect glass of Allagash White in the comfort of your own home? Mike is here to show you how to properly "rouse your yeast" for the optimal experience with our favorite witbier.

Have other beer-related questions? Let us know!

node.text: We join Mike at Eventide Oyster Company to tell us a little bit about how to get started with briny bivalves.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Allagash Brewing Company on September 17, 2021. May be an image of camera.

node.text: You'll make more memories if you take the scenic way. The beauty of the landscape here in Maine inspired us to make Scenic Way, a dry and drinkable farmhouse-style ale. Brewed with local grains, fermented with saison yeast, and dry hopped for a splash of aromatics, it's our ode to savoring the sights and sounds of the scenery surrounding you. You'll find this beer in four-packs of 16 oz. at the brewery and in cans across a few states up near us, including MA, ME, NH, NY, and VT, at your local @hannafordmkts.

node.text: There’s a difference between drinking beer and tasting beer. And during Hop Culture’s Beers With(out) Beards Festival this Saturday (9/18), we’ll be helping to show you the difference. At 2:45pm EST, our very own Lindsay—Certified Cicerone and our Tour and Tasting Specialist, and Emily—Tasting Room Manager—will be hosting a beer tasting session during this celebration of women in craft beer. To tune in and taste along, just grab a beer and head to @hopculturemag. The virtual festivities start at 1pm EST.

node.text:
Each year on Halloween night, we brew a certain beer. It rests and cools overnight in our coolship, and legend has it that ghosts, spirits, and ghouls float through the windows of our coolship shed and haunt the beer. This story is, frankly, quite absurd. We brew it with freshly smashed pumpkin, pumpkin seeds, and molasses, then ferment and blend it after a number of years spent in oak barrels. (Without ghosts.) It's a wild beer, featuring a unique touch of caramelized malt, with a slightly tart flavor that finishes deliciously dry in your human mouth. We call this beer Ghoulschip, and it releases at the brewery this Thursday, with select states receiving small drops of it here and there. In conclusion, we promise there are no ghosts or ghouls involved in any way. 

Respectfully, 

The Allagash Coolship Ghost

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Allagash Brewing Company in Allagash Brewing Company with @greatamericanbeerfestival. May be an image of drink.

node.text: We’re excited as heck after hearing we won Brewery of the Year in our category at the Great American Beer Festival. We’re also very proud to see both Allagash White and Tripel win silver medals. Knowing the passion and hard work so many of our fellow breweries put into this industry, we are grateful and humbled to be recognized. We also want to give a shoutout to our entire team for the dedication and determination they've put in this year on all fronts. Their optimism, adaptability, and enthusiasm are a constant source of inspiration.

node.text: We went up to The County—Aroostook County, Maine, to be specific. About 4.5 hours north of Portland, it’s the largest county east of the Mississippi and where most of our local grain comes from. We got to see Sarah & Marcus of @auroramillsfarm, an organic farm that provides us with oats for beers like Sixteen Counties, River Trip, and Allagash White. Then we were off to visit with the Buck Family, who have been farming since 1958. On top of showing us around their land—they have an entire field dedicated solely to white wheat for Allagash White—they cooked us up a hearty homemade meal. In the world of brewing, there are few things more rewarding than building lasting friendships with the people who have dedicated themselves to growing the best possible ingredients for our beer.
